   ____  _   _
  |  _ \| |_| |__                     GNU Pth - Multi-Scheduler Fork
  | |_) | __| '_ \                    Portable cooperative threads,
  |  __/| |_| | | |                    now M:N across multiple CPUs.
  |_|    \__|_| |_|

  ABOUT THIS FORK

  This is a modernized fork of GNU Pth (Ralf S. Engelschall's Portable
  Threads). Classic Pth multiplexes many cooperative "green" threads onto
  a SINGLE OS thread on a single CPU. This fork adds a multi-scheduler
  (M:N) mode: N independent cooperative schedulers, each on its own OS
  thread, so green threads run in parallel on multiple cores -- while
  still being written as straight-line, blocking-style code through Pth's
  native API (or its optional POSIX pthreads emulation).

  You still write ordinary sequential code -- pth_read() just returns
  bytes -- but the library can now use more than one CPU, wait on large
  numbers of descriptors efficiently via epoll(7)/kqueue(2), and switch
  contexts portably (including Apple Silicon) via Boost.Context.

  The full design, rationale, memory model, benchmarks and analysis are
  in MULTISCHED-DESIGN.md.

  KEY ENHANCEMENTS OVER UPSTREAM 2.0.7

  o  Multi-scheduler M:N threading (PTH_MP): N cooperative schedulers on
     N OS threads; green threads pinned to a home scheduler. New API:
     pth_mp_init(), pth_mp_shutdown(), pth_spawn_on(), pth_sched_id().
  o  Every thread-control primitive works across schedulers: mutex
     (incl. fair ownership handoff), condition variable, rwlock, barrier,
     join, cancel/abort/raise, suspend/resume/yield, message ports, once.
  o  Scalable fd-readiness backends: persistent-registration epoll(7)
     (Linux) and kqueue(2) (*BSD/macOS), with poll(2)/select(2) retained
     as close-safe fallbacks. The native backend is the per-platform
     default.
  o  Portable context switching via Boost.Context fcontext ("bctx"),
     required on macOS/Apple Silicon where ucontext(3) is unusable.
  o  Documented SMP memory model built on acquire/release atomics and
     validated under ThreadSanitizer.
  o  Modern CMake build with continuous integration on Linux, FreeBSD and
     macOS; the classic autoconf/libtool build has been removed.
  o  Platform scope narrowed to current targets (below); the legacy
     setjmp/sigaltstack machine-context "dispatch zoo" for long-dead
     platforms has been removed.

  SUPPORTED PLATFORMS

  CPU:  x86_64 (Intel/AMD 64-bit) and arm64 / aarch64.
  OS:   Linux, FreeBSD, macOS.

  Machine-context method:
    o  mcsc  -  ucontext(3); default on Linux and FreeBSD.
    o  bctx  -  Boost.Context (vendored fcontext assembly); default on
                macOS, and selectable on any target.

  Build system:
    o  CMake  -  the only build system; supports all targets and both
                 context methods; exercised by CI. See INSTALL.

  BUILDING

    cmake -S . -B build -DPTH_BUILD_TESTS=ON
    cmake --build build
    ctest --test-dir build --output-on-failure

  Notable options: -DPTH_MP=ON (multi-scheduler; default ON),
  -DPTH_SCHED_EPOLL / -DPTH_SCHED_KQUEUE (native readiness backend;
  default per platform), -DPTH_MCTX_MTH=mcsc|bctx, and
  -DPTH_BUILD_PTHREAD=ON (POSIX pthreads emulation; default OFF).

  DOCUMENTATION

  o  MULTISCHED-DESIGN.md  -  full design of the M:N fork (architecture,
     backends, memory model, benchmarks, comparison with other runtimes).
  o  pth(3) man page (pth.pod / pth.3)  -  the API reference.
  o  REVIEW.md  -  code-review history and resolutions.

